  "13-4": (
    caption: [Some common reactions that form and break COC bonds in biological systems. For both the aldol condensation and the Claisen condensation, a carbanion serves as nucleophile and the carbon of a carbonyl group serves as electrophile. The carbanion is stabilized in each case by another carbonyl at the adjoining carbon. In the decarbox- ylation reaction, a carbanion is formed on the carbon shaded blue as the CO2 leaves. The reaction would not occur at an appreciable rate without the stabilizing effect of the carbonyl adjacent to the carbanion carbon. Wherever a carbanion is shown, a stabilizing resonance with the adjacent carbonyl, as shown in Figure 13–3b, is assumed. An imine (Fig. 13–3c) or other electron-withdrawing group (including certain enzymatic cofactors such as pyridoxal) can replace the carbonyl group in the stabilization of carbanions.],
